@node About this Software
@chapter About this Software
@cindex About this Software

This software is similar to BATTLETECH ® A Game of Armored Combat.

"Strap yourself into the ultimate suit of armor -- the BattleMech:
thirty feet tall and weighing up to a hundred tons. This humanoid
engine of destruction you control is a walking arsenal with enough
firepower to level a city. The BattleTech game system takes you into
the world of the 31st century, where war has become a way of life,
and great empires and tiny factions struggle among themselves for
control of humankind."

A Brief History of the BattleTech Universe.

In the years immediately following the second World War, the Virtual
Geographic League (TM) gradually began to re-emerge as an active scientific
institution. Many of the leading atomic scientists and engineers of the day
recoiled in horror at the weapons of mass destruction that they helped to
create. The VGL offered a much-needed home to those seeking peaceful
applications for these powerful new technologies.

One of these men was George Markov, J. Robert Oppenheimer's chief
lieutenant on the Manhattan Project and the man principally responsible
for the engineering breakthrough which turned Einstein's theories into
reality. Due to his impassioned pacifist speeches to the House Un-American
Activities Committee, Markov was essentially unemployable when Einstein
invited him to lecture at Princeton in 1949. Within six months, he was
running VGL Labs and sending unmanned camera ships on split-second
reconnaissance missions.

At the same time on the other side of the world, a young jet-jockey
named Sid Mandlebaum was making a name for himself in the skies over Korea.
There was more to this pilot than an unusual name -- he was the first Jewish
graduate of West Point, a military man by trade, and he shot down six MIGs
in a single 1952 mission. He was also the youngest colonel in the armed
services when Lindbergh recruited him into the VGL in 1959. Mandlebaum
gave the name "BattleTech" to the futuristic technology he saw in the
Unv.-137 camera pod photos. During this time Einstein and Markov were able
to discover a consistent link to dozens of human colonies in space some two
thousand years into the future, emboldening the League to chance new manned
missions. On his third mission Mandlebaum became the first VGL pilot to
exit his vehicle while in a virtual world. On his fourteenth mission, he
disappeared.

When a VGL reconnaissance team finally found Mandlebaum a decade later
he had gone completely native, having embarked on a new life as an elite
Master MechWarrior. While he refused to return to our world, he did provide
numerous technical documents he had been collecting along with a book he
authored: Inside the BattleTech Universe.
These technical manuals have enabled the VGL and its pilots to achieve safe
and consistent translocations into any one of the dozens of
Inner Sphere BattleMechs (TM). Our gratitude to him is immeasurable and
his deeds will live long in the storied history of the VGL. Sid's only
request to the Board of Directors was that we look after his family here
on Earth - a duty we do proudly.

@node The Unit Window
@chapter The Unit Window
@cindex The Unit Window

The main window you see is the Unit window. Units come in different flavors. 
There are Player Units which can only have Player characters in them, 
and NPC Units which can have both Player and NPC characters. 
Units have a fixed number of Warriors, either 4, 8, 12, 24 or 36. 
Player Units can have up to 50 Warrior, Technician and Mech files. 
NPC Units don't change. The best way to play the game is to 
start in a good NPC Unit until you gain a little experience. 
Then you can branch out and form your own player Unit.

In addition to player vs NPC Unit, there are also Mercenary vs House
Units. A Mercenary Unit sells it services to a House, under a contract.
It must fulfill its contract before it changes employer or lose reputation.
A Mercenary Unit that does not have a contract has no way to get more money
from repairs other than through combat. The contract will specify how much
the Unit will be paid per combat point, how many combat points the Unit must
earn to complete it contract, what percentage of the combat damage the House
will pay and what percentage of the Salvage the Unit may keep. Mercenary
Units must find their own replacements for lost mechs. A House Unit is given
everything, all repairs, replacement mechs, etc. In exchange a House Unit
can never change employer, warriors are paid a straight salary, and they do
not collect salvage.

To form a Unit, use the pulldown menu and select "New...".
In the upcomming window you must at least enter a name for the new Unit.
If you do not specify a Warrior as the leader for a Unit,
the Unit will have no C-Bills at all.
Once the Unit is formed new characters must 'Join' the Unit, and a roll 
is required for acceptance. Make sure to setup the contracts for the Unit 
and its individual warriors before you start adding members. Make sure you 
name the Unit before you try to get a contract. Player Units and NPC Units 
will be allowed to set the starting size of the Unit and its reputation.

Whenever you load a Unit all Destroyed mechs will be removed.

In a listview selector you will see a list of all warriors, mechs and 
technicians. Sometimes you will see a '*' behind characters and Mechs names.
This will show you that a character and its Mech are out on patrol and are
currently not available. A '#' behind characters and Mechs names will
indicate that a character has been injured or a Mech has been damaged.
If one of the characters has died then a '+' will apear behind the
name of that character.

You can change the Unit Name by clicking in the name gadget.

"Add Character" allows you to add members to the Unit to replace lost 
characters. "Remove Character" allows you to remove a member of the Unit.
The person removed will be saved to disk as an individual character and 
can be used somewhere else or deleted.
Characters that are using a Mech will be removed with the Mech they are
assigned to. 

"Buy new Mech" allows you to buy new Mechs for the Unit. Characters can
change to that Mech. Another way to get Mechs is to salvage them after a
won combat.

"Unit Stores" allows you to buy replacement parts for your mechs. 
The purpose is to provide a system for campaignes. You can buy Units 
stores for a campaign and then worry about running out of the parts 
you need to keep your mechs in working condition.

