@node Player Characters
@section Player Characters
@cindex Player Characters

Player characters, Warriors, Technicians, etc. roll for their starting
character points and start off as zero level, or green characters.
The number of character points a character gets at the beginning will vary
randomly. You can try as often as you want, but if you are playing in a
group you should establish ground rules. Around here we allow a person 
two chances at a character.

Once you have a character created you can use the initial character points
to upgrade character attributes and skills.
You can 'buy' abilities and skills for your character.
Later, you will be able to exchange experience for more character points to
further improve your character.

"Body" is the amount of damage the character can take. Your character
hit points is ten times your Body. Body affects your physical skills such as
Brawling and Survival. "Dexterity" is how well you move, yours sense of
balance and your eye hand coordination. It affects your weapons abilities
and piloting abilities. "Learn" is how easily you can pick up technical
skills, such as piloting, leadership and mech repair. Learn also determines
how many skills your character can 'learn'. You are allowed one skill for
each point of Learn and you allowed four skill levels for each point of
Learn. "Charisma" is how other people see you, physically and personality.
This attribute affects your ability to deal with other people, such as
leadership. For a pilot Dexterity and Learn are the most important since
they determine you piloting skill and gunnery skill. For a technician Learn
is the most important since in determines your ability to repair mechs.

@node NPC Characters
@section NPC Characters
@cindex NPC Characters

NPC characters are just like Player characters except you can make them
any level you want. On the other hand they are FIXED characters. They do not
go up in level and can never be changed after they are created. 

@node Healing Characters
@section Healing Characters
@cindex Healing Characters

A injured character can be healed. The higher the Rank of the character 
the higher the amount of C-Bills you need for healing.

If your character is Dead, held Hostage or out in a
combat somewhere a requester will inform you. If your character is out you
will be asked if you want to bring him home. It cost 5000 C-Bills to bring a
character back and will be counted as a lose combat.
You should be careful doing it. If your character is in a
Saved Game somewhere and you bring him back, later, when you finish the game,
your old character will overwrite anything you do to the one that you brought
back. The idea is not to have two copies of your character running around.

@node Training Characters
@section Training Characters
@cindex Training Characters

Characters can be trained if they have enough
character points. To earn character points you must convert available
experience points earned in combat. Every character can be trained in
all skills. The maximal skill level for all skills depends on 
@dfn{Learn Ability}.

@node Advance to next level
@section Advance to next level
@cindex Advance to next level

If a character has enough experience points he can advance to the next 
Rank. This will give him additional character points that can 
be used for buying skills. There are 4 Ranks and several Elite levels.

Ranking and experience points needed:

@itemize @bullet
@item @dfn{Green}   -        0-2500 experience points;
@item @dfn{Regular} -    2500-15000 experience points;
@item @dfn{Veteran} -  15000-100000 experience points;
@item @dfn{Elite}   - 100000-300000 experience points;
@item @dfn{Elite 1} - 300000-400000 experience points;
@item Next Elite Rank     +100000 experience points;
@end itemize

The only Update available for NPC characters is to change
Units or, if he has lost a mech, to get a new mech.

@node Upgrade Character Attributes
@section Upgrade Character Attributes
@cindex Upgrade Character Attributes

There are 4 character Attributes: 
Body, Dexterity, Learn Ability and Charisma.
They describe the personality of a character. Every attribute
will give a character special abilities. There are 12 levels in
each Attribute. Body is needed to survive and affects the hit
points of a character. Dexterity will give a character the ability to
act better as a Technician. Learn Ability affects the maximum
skill level allowed for all character skills. Charisma allows
a character to act better as a Mech Warrior. These attributes
will be randomized when you create new characters and will give them
their special personality.

@node Upgrade Character Skills
@section Upgrade Character Skills
@cindex Upgrade Character Skills

There are 24 skills in that a character can be trained. 
Each skill has 12 levels. To upgrade a skill the character 
needs character points.

A Mech Warrior will buy all Gunnery, Mech and Piloting skills first.
A Technician will need also everything that has to do with repairing 
Mechs and tuning engines and weapons. 
Leaders of a Unit must be trained in combat Tactics and Leadership too.
Consider well which skills your character will need first and save
charcter points for these skills. 

@node Convert Experience Points
@section Convert Experience Points
@cindex Convert Experience Points

The available experience points are the experience points
you have earned in combat. These experience points are also used
in combat for modifying weapons and skill rolls.
You can convert this experience points to character points
which you need to buy skills.
It is adviced to have some experience points left for modifying
weapons and skill rolls when they are needed.

@node Change Mech
@section Change Mech
@cindex Change Mech

All characters can be assigned to a Mech. If a Unit owns more Mechs
then currently assigned, a character can change to one of these Mechs.

@node Buy Xtended Mech
@section Buy Xtended Mech
@cindex Buy Xtended Mech

Characters with lots of C-Bills can buy one
of 9 special designed Mechs contained in Headquarters. This
Mechs are exclusively contained in Headquarters. Some of
this Mechs are also contained on disk but are not as powerful
these. A lot of them can't be modified further more.
Every Mech has its own special power.

@node The Factory Window
@chapter The Factory Window
@cindex The Factory Window

In the Factory window the design of your combat Mech is entirely up to you.
Its design should be a compromise between weight, speed, armor and weapons.
In addition, the Factory can be used to repair damaged mechs and to Salvage 
badly damaged mechs. It is adviced to use Technicians in the Factory,
they can earn some experience points here.

The main Factory window will display the current mech in three areas.
The top left area lists all the armor for the mech, the point value of its 
internal structure and where all the internal components are located. 
Each dot or letter represents one internal location. This is where your 
W)eapons, A)mmo and H)eat Sinks will be
installed. It also shows your where your E)ngine and G)yro are located in
the center torso. J)ump J)ets and F)uel are located in the side torsos. The
head contains the C)ockpit for the pilot, L)ife support systems and weapon
S)ensors. An "x" indicates an arm or leg actuator and a "." indicates an
empty location. 

@itemize @bullet
@item @dfn{W} - Weapon;
@item @dfn{A} - Ammo;
@item @dfn{H} - Heat Sink;
@item @dfn{P} - Power Jump;
@item @dfn{F} - Full Jump;
@item @dfn{E} - Engine;
@item @dfn{G} - Gyro;
@item @dfn{L} - Life Support;
@item @dfn{C} - Cockpit;
@item @dfn{S} - Sensor;
@end itemize

The bottom area lists all weapons selected for your mech
along with statistics for the weapons. The first two letters indicate where
the weapon is mounted (if its mounted). So HD would be head, CT, center
torso, etc. If there is an "*" in front of the name that indicates the the
weapon is mounted to fire backwards.
After that you will see the weapon name, the amount of
ammo available for that weapon, damage produced when it hits a
target, heat produced when firing this weapon and the maximum
and minimum range, if any, for a weapon. If a weapon needs
no ammo, as Lasers do, you will not see the ammo available for
that weapon.

If something has been damaged you will see a '-' in the Mech
structure and a '--' in the weapon list.

Sometimes you will notice that some mech-parts
have changed its colors. The color stands for:

@itemize @bullet
@item @dfn{Black}  - Good condition
@item @dfn{Yellow} - Warning on condition
@item @dfn{Red}    - Danger on condition
@end itemize

Any damaged areas will appear in Red.

In the lower right corner of the window you will see the combat 
classification information about your mech. You can use it as a
relative measure of the strength of a mech.
The size of a Mech is a indicator for the weight in
tons of a Mech and it special class. The engine size describes
the power the fusion engine has. Weapon Capability is the
maximum damage produced on an opponent when firing all the
weapons this Mech has at once. Melee Capability describes the
capability this Mech has in hand to hand combat. Defense Capability
tells you how many armour this Mech has and how long a Warrior
can defend himself when he is under attack. Finally cost describes
the amount of C-Bills needed when buying such a Mech.

