@node Repair Mech
@section Repair Mech
@cindex Repair Mech

Normally a Technician is used to repair Mechs, but also other characters
are able to repair a Mech if they have been trained in technician skills.
A repair roll is performed everytime one of your characters is trying to
repair a Mech. The computer will check with your
technician to see if the item is repairable. If it is not repairable you
will have take a replacement part out of Unit Stores or, if you are using a
Warrior, buy a new part. Replacement is guaranteed to work, but cost 10
times as much as repair. Repair is a lot cheaper than replacement, but it
may not work the first time. You can try to repair as often as you want as
long as you don't damage the part beyond repair. Depending on how good your
technician is, there is a small chance that a repaired item may fail during
combat. The Technician gets experience for each successful repair. For
Units the cost to repair and re-arm your mech may be paid in part or in full
by your employer, depending on you Unit contract.

@node Re-arm Weapon
@section Re-arm Weapon
@cindex Re-arm Weapon

"Reload" checks the current mech and replaces all ammo used in combat.
It is an all or nothing item. You can't partially reload ammo. For Unit,
the correct ammo must be available in Unit Stores.

@node Mount Weapon
@section Mount Weapon
@cindex Mount Weapon

"Mount" allows you to arm your combat Mech. You will see a list of all 
weapons available along with their weight, damage, heat generated and 
ammo rounds/ton. Add a weapon by clicking on the weapon. Select the mount
area for the weapona and the mount area for the ammo, if any.

To mount a weapon in the back direction,
hold down the right mouse button and select the mount area in the
appropriate menu by clicking with the left mouse button.

The mounted location is shown in the listview before the
name. An asterick '*' indicates that the weapon is pointed backward.

@node Remove Weapon
@section Remove Weapon
@cindex Remove Weapon

"Remove" will remove a weapon from your weapons list and
unmount it if necessary. 

@node Modify Weapon
@section Modify Weapon
@cindex Modify Weapon

With "Modify" you can change the ammo, the damage and
the heat produced if a weapon is fired, the minimal and maximal
range and the critical hit for a weapon. You must select a weapon
in the listview for doing this.

@node New Mech Creation
@section New Mech Creation
@cindex New Mech Creation

Select "New..." from the menuand a 20 Ton Mech will be created.
This Mech will have neither weapons nor body armour.
Creating new Mechs is almost free, if you are a Mercenary or House Unit.
Otherwise you have to supply all the internal components in the Unit
Stores.

You can modify this mech to your hearts content. 
You can not modify Armor, Heat Sinks or Jump Jets that are damaged. 
As a general rule everything should be repaired before you modify. 
If you modify a damaged mech your total weight
may be too heavy when you finally repair the damage.

In fact if your actual weight goes more than five tons over your frame weight, your frame
weight will be automatically increased by five tons. You can have a mech
with a little extra weight. These tend to be a little unstable in combat
with better piloting skill needed to control them on occasion.

The "Image" of the Mech should be changed. 
You can select the image your mech will use during the game by clicking on
the image you want. The image you selected will appear in the main window.

Once you have your weight the next thing you should get is the "Engine".
There are only certain engines available. The engine power determines the
speed of your mech. The speed of a mech is the time, in seconds, that a mech
will take to move one plain hex. The other pair of numbers tells you how
many plain hexes you can walk or run in 100 seconds.

"Jump Jets" allow your mech to jump into the air. This is a BIG
advantage in combat at close range. How far you can jump is determined by
how far you can walk. You can jump the same number of hexes that you walk in
100 seconds. The number for jump is the number of hexes under perfect
conditions. It gets less for heat and damage.

"Heat Sinks" get rid of the heat your mech generates. Heat is your
worse enemy. All mechs have 12 heat sinks as part of the engine and you can
add more. You can "Change" and "Install" the number of heat sinks you
want, but only the amount of free spares "." is allowed. This is done
automatically for you.
To remove a heat sink just move the slider in the other direction.

"Armor" is critical to your mech. It protects your delicate weapons and
other internal components from damage. The armor menu item has
11 slider gadgets, one for each armor location.
There is a maximum amount of armor allowed for the head. 
One ton of armor gives 16 pts of protection.

"Hands" is an optional item. You can remove the hand and wrist actuators.
This will give you two extra spaces in the arms for weapons, but you will 
not be able to pick up anything with that arm.

Make sure you give your combat Mech a name
and make sure you Save it before you Quit. It will be saved with the mechs
name plus its weight. There are currently 8 Mech classes contained in the 
Light, Medium, Heavy, Assault and Xtended directories.
You will be given a warning if you have forgotten to
mount any of your weapons.

@node Light Mechs
@section Light Mechs
@cindex Light Mechs

Heres where I differ from a lot of people in tactics. When I create a light
mech, it is usually for the Kamikaze/suicide missions. Strap as much high
explosive ammo as you can on the thing, make it REALY fast (walk of 8 or
so) and go for it!

I know people use them for other things. But tell me this -- how much
armour and weapons can you shove onto a 20 ton mech? Not much. You might as
well use it as an "ammo" mech. Set it up as I said before, and get it to
run like hell at its target. Then overheat or something to blow the crap
out of it, destroying it -- but blowing up everything in the nearby
vicinity as well.

@node Medium Mechs
@section Medium Mechs
@cindex Medium Mechs

Creating Medium mechs can be a difficult job, since you need to decide
between many factors like speed, armour and weapons. Choosing one as
important can make other factors suffer badly. I have created many medium
mechs bedly, since I put faith in the wrong areas for the battle I was up
against.

Make the mech quick, but do not spend more than about 10 tons on the
engine. This will vary according to the size of the mech, but I feel that
this is a good starting point. Next, consider some of the upgraded armour
and structures provided in the 3rd edition rules if you follow them. They
can save a couple of tons here and there, and this can mean that you are
better armed ao armoured. One good idea is usually the upgraded internal
structure (if available).

Also, you might want to consider jump jets for this mech. The Death
fromabove tactic can work quite well if you do (I have used it to good
effect a number of times).

After that, you can start adding weapons, Medium lasers are my favorite,
but you may have different choices. Just make it medium range weapons,
light and little heat. The less heat your weapons generate, the longer you
will be able to charge your opponent.

As for ammo, make sure you put in CASE if you are an Inner Sphere mech
(clan mechs get this as standard -- and you say you prefer the IS stuff)
since you will have less armour than an assault mech, and an ammo explosion
can easily accur.

@node Heavy Mechs
@section Heavy Mechs
@cindex Heavy Mechs

I have found that the best thing for a heavy mech is an AC/10 or 2. An
AC/20 takes up far too much space, and I usually find LRM's to be too
unpredictable and unreliable for any real damage to be done with them. I
still make use of SRM's (particularly Infernos) since they are a much
better weapon for the amount of heat they cost to run.

The next thing that you need to consider is armour. I find that about 9-10
tons is usually sufficient. Other things that I find useful are Medium
lasers. Put a couple in where ever you can spare them. Don't waste your
time with smal lasers! They are far too short a range weapon. If you are
going to use them, you had better be good close quaters combat. You are
much better off by getting a couple of Medium lasers. They do more damage,
have better range, and don't give off much heat for the damage they do.

Other weaponary to consider is a PPC (Plasma cannon). Just the one of them,
particulary if you are in the Clans, will aide your cause quite well.
Unforetunately, They do generate a lot of heat, but do a lot of
CONCENTRATED damage. They also have a very good range.

As for Ammunition, you will need to decide how important the weapons that
require ammo are. Usually, when you get to assigning ammo, you will not
have the much space left, and so not get as much ammo on board as you would
like. If that is the case, then you will need to look at which weapons can
give you the best advantage particularly in the early stages of the battle.
This is usually long range weapons like an AC/10 or LRM's.

@node Assault Mechs
@section Assault Mechs
@cindex Assault Mechs

To create an assault mech you must work out what strengths you want it to
have. Should it be covered in armour? Or should it be covered in big guns?
Or something in between?

I find that a speed of 3 or 4 is a necissity for a assault mech, so an XL
engine (if you use those rules) is essential. The only problem with this is
if you are creating an Inner Sphere Mech is that you cannot have an AC/20
or variant on the mech if you use an XL engine. Oh well, I never liked
Inner Sphere anyways. I find them to be akward to use, since the weapons
and armour are almost always heavier per unit than for the clan mechs.

Anyway, I find that at least one or two ERPPC's are not just useful, but
essential. I also find that apart from Heat seekers and Infernos --
missiles are almost no use. If you have the Tactical Handbook, then you
will find a whole heap of new weapons to use. These weapons are mainly
available to the Inner Sphere, but some of the weapons can be used by the
Clans.

As for armour, it really depends on what you want. Make sure you allow at
least 10 tons for armour, since assault mechs tend to take quite a beating
battle.

@node Damaging Mechs
@section Damaging Mechs
@cindex Damaging Mechs

Why would you want to deliberately damage a mech? There are two
reasons. First of all, you might want to create a scenario in which a Unit
has received combat damage and has not had time for repair or only partial
repair. Secondly, you might have been sabataged. This would leave your mech
in faulty condition, but not failed. You can't repair sabatage until it
fails. You CAN deliberately damage the weak part and then repair it.

Make sure you save your Warrior or Unit file after you have made your
repairs.

@node Mech Salvage
@section Mech Salvage
@cindex Mech Salvage

"Salvage Mech" strips a Mech down to its component parts and gives the
Unit or Warrior C-Bills in return, see your contract for salvage rights.
It is designed to get rid of mechs that
have been too badly damaged in combat to be worth repairing. This is the
main way to get rid of a mech so that the warrior can try for a new mech. It
is also the main way to get rid of extra mechs captured in combat.

@node Modify Engine Size
@section Modify Engine Size
@cindex Modify Engine Size

Engines will give Mechs its power to run and walk
quickly in the terrain. Heavy Mechs with small engines will be
slightly slow. Light Mechs with big engines will be rather fast.
When modifying engines the weight will change with the power of the
engine. Engines with power greater than 390 will weight over 50 tons.
Due to the fact, the size of a Mech will change with the engine size.
If you notice that the size of the fusion engine will not be enough to
speed up your Mech than you need to modify the engine speed.

@node Modify Engine Speed
@section Modify Engine Speed
@cindex Modify Engine Speed

If a Mech is to slow when running and walking
in the terrain than here you can enhance the engine to be more
efficient. The maximum speed you can achieve in this way will
differ from the size of the engine and the size of a Mech.
Light Mechs will get less modify advantage then heavy and
very slow Mechs.

@node Modify Jump Jets
@section Modify Jump Jets
@cindex Modify Jump Jets

Jump Jets are the most powerful add ones for
every Mech. They will allow a Mech to jump in the air and jump
over hills, forests and deep water. Jump Jets will be used to
scout for enemy Mechs and objects hidden in the terrain. If
the enemy has been hidden behind a mountain or in deep forests
you can use your Jump Jets to scout and destroy them. But the
use of Jump Jets will make you a easy target for the enemy.
Jump Jets needs free room to be mounted to a Mech. If your Mech
has no free spares available in its Mech structure no Jump
Jets can be mounted.

@node Modify Heat Sinks
@section Modify Heat Sinks
@cindex Modify Heat Sinks

Everything in a Mech produces heat. Heat will
be produced by the weapons you are carrying, when running or
walking or form a damaged engine. Fire in the forests and
explosions in the surroundings of a Mech will also produce heat.
For all this reasons your Mech needs extra Heat Sinks. As the
Jump Jets Heat Sinks will need spare room in your Mech structure
when adding one.

@node Modify Body Armour
@section Modify Body Armour
@cindex Modify Body Armour

Body armour will protect a Mech from enemy
attack. A Mech with no body armour will be soon destroyed.
Most important part of a Mech that needs to be protected
is the head of a Mech. The head of a Mech is the place where
the Mech Warrior will sit in his cockpit and control every
part of a Mech. Add here all you can get of armour. There are
weapons which will blast your head (and the warrior in it)
away with only one shot so watch out.
Internal structures are another type of armour. They are not
as effective as body armour since the weapons, ammo, Heat Sinks,
Power Jumps, engine and gyros are unprotected, but they will
simply hold the Mech parts together. Internal structures will
change with the size of a Mech. Heavy Mechs have more internal
structures than light Mechs.

@node Preferences
@chapter Preferences
@cindex Preferences

The Headquarters and MechForce Programms share a config file called 
"MechForce.cfg". They will look for it in the "$PROGDIR" directory. It works
like the old config file except it has new options and can't be easily edited
with a text editor. The Preferences window has several string gadgets for
all the necessary file paths. In addition to the file paths you can specify
the recycle time for ALL weapons. A negative number "-1" will give you the
current (preferred) defaults. You can toggle on and off "Aimed Shots". This
will reduce the number of head shots during the game. You can specify the
delay time for messages and the speed of missiles. You can specify the color
for each side. That means ANY color, but only RED and BLACK work well
(but try it for yourself). You can disable the save at the end of the 
game. This turns ALL combat modes into training/simulation.

If you turn saborage on Headquarters will sabotage
every Mech that you load or modify in Headquarters.
Sabotage may now occur during combat missions and patrol. The basic
sabotage that is always done is sabotaging internal structures.
It may occur if a character is asked to perform a skill roll depending on
the condition occured in combat, like kicking and punching.
If succesfull no dammage will occur. Other sabotage is on weapon.
Here the character must perform a skill roll everytime the sabotaged
weapon is fired. If successfull no damage will occur.

If you select the 'Save Unit' option, Headquarters will save the 
current Unit to disk if you exit from the programm. 

@node Battle Bible
@chapter Battle Bible
@cindex Battle Bible

By now you should be familiar with basic Mech operation. You should be able
to start one up and move around and shoot at targets. So now it is the time
for you to begin training in tactics and techniques. This document will
attempt to point out several of these and help you prepare for your Trail
of Position, as well as actual combat. Note that while I have tried to be
as generic as possible, the whole reason behind most of this is based on
the situations you will encounter in the Trail. But, you will face many
different situations as a mechwarrior. And so it is my hope that you will
use this as an example of how to prepare for any situation. Read this,
memorize this, worship this, and never leave home without it.

