@node Training
@section Training
@cindex Training

There are some basic things to focus on while you are training. While there
are many more in addition to this, here are some that may not be obvious to
you if you have not played BattleTech before.

@itemize @bullet
@item Watch the bearings and headings closely. Know where your enemy is in
relation to you, and where they are going. This will help you either avoid
them or intercept them, as the case may be. A useful thing to do for those
of you who are not so faliliar with using degrees is to keep a diagram of
the cardinal compass headings and their degree equivalents. 
[Note: North: 0, NorthEast: 60, East: 90, SouthEast: 120, South: 180, 
SouthWest: 240, West: 270, NorthWest:300]
Set this bseide you while you are simming and refer to it as needed.

@item Know where you are at all times. How far from the edge of the map are
you? Are you headed into a lake? Watch your tactical. If you hit the edge,
you asking for trouble.

@item If you have the ability, set your keypad to be the heading macros So
if you hit 7, it will set your heading to 300, 2 would set it to 180, etc.
Note that in hex, moving directly northwest is 300, not 315. When in doubt,
use the BEARING command.

@item Practice, Practice, Practice. Nothing is better. The more you sim,
the easier it is to keep track of all the things you need to keep track of.
@end itemize

@node Preparation
@section Preparation
@cindex Preparation

@itemize @bullet
@item Map:

Before entering any hostile situation a good strategist will try to learn
as much as possible about it beforehand. Get intelligence reports of the
map onto which you will be moving. Study it, and find strategic locations
that will be useful in combat. Water, hills, trees, and buildings are all
useful. Also know where the open spaces and clear runnings lanes are, so
you can pic a direction to move in without having to worry too much about
running into something.

@item Your Mech:

Any good Mech piolot knows the full potential and specs of his or her Mech.

@itemize @bullet
@item Know your top speed and walking speed.

@item Know your weapon numbers so you can SIGHT them and fire them
individually -- do not overheat by firing them all at once. Use TICs when
you are in a critical situation, (i.e. they are right on top of you) or
when you know your heat is not a problem.

@item Know your weapon specs. What is the maximum range you can fire? What
range is medium range for your weapons? Remember that you have a better
chance to hit if you are in a short range bracket. Is your Mech mainly a
long or short range Mech?

@item Know where your weapons are located on your Mech. How effective will
you be if you happen to loose your left arm? Do you have any rear-firing
weapons?

@itemize @bullet
@item Look where your ammo is stored, and how much of it you have. Ration
your ammo according to how much you have and how many foes you are facing.
If you have 80 SRMs it is not a bad thing to fire them with an 11 or 12 to
hit, as you will probably take too much damage and have them explode inside
of you before you can fire them all. Be prepared to dump ammo that is in a
section that has been severely damaged. If you don't need it, it's better
not to take the risk of it exploding.

@item It is probably in your best intrest to dump your Machine Gun
ammunition, as if you are close enough to use it, you have probably already
been hurt enough to put it in severe danger of being hit and exploding.

@item Feel free to fire your energy weapons (weapons that don't use
ammunition) even with a high ToHit early on. Wether you get lucky and hit
with them  could very well be the deciding factor of the outcome of the
battle. 

@end itemize

@item Know how much armor you have. Can you afford to take risks? If you
are in a Dasher, you might want to be very cautious, while a Daishi should
be more willing to take some hits. Pay close attention to how much rear
armor you have.

@item Know your jump capacity. Can you jump? How far? Utilize your jump
jets; they are a very advantagous tool for getting around terrain or
getting away from/closer to enemies.

@end itemize

@item Enemy Mech(s):

If you know what you will be going up against, by all means study the enemy
Mechs and know all of the above things. If not, (and you usually wont),
scan the enemy Mechs as soon as you possibly can make a mental note of all
the above thngs that you can see. Plan your strategy around how effective
they are at a long and short range.

@end itemize

@node Terrain
@section Terrain
@cindex Terrain

Using terrain effectively is one of the most important things you can do.
By moving in and out of your enemy's Line of Sight (LOS), you can keep them
gussing as to what you are doing. The method of using terrain depends on
your mission and situation.

@itemize @bullet
@item If you outnumber your enemy, it may be best to take a defensive
position in trees or in water. Force them to move to you in the open where
you can get good free shots on them.

@item If you are outnumbered, you may not want to sit somewhere or you will
be surrounded and overhelmed. Thus , you will want to move around hills and
tree lines. You should know what types of terrain block a LOS or provide
partial cover (trees, hills, buildings) and how to use them to do so.

@itemize @bullet
@item Be wary of enemies with jump jets, as they will be able to spot you
even if you are behind a large Building.

@item If they do not have jump jets, or not using them often, you can
really keep them guessing by moving out of their LOS and then abruptly
changing your direction. They will often be moving to intercept your
orginal heading while you are off moving the other direction. This is good
if you are trying to keep your distance, or if you want to surprise them
and come at them from the back/side.

@item Always know where you are going and what the terrain is in front of
you. Using LRS is a good way to plan where you will move next. Use TACTICAL
to steer more finely.

@end itemize

@item Know the effects of walking through terrain.

@itemize @bullet
@item If speed is your main priority, you should avoid walking through
terrain. You will slow down considerably.

@item Trees are probably okay, because they provide partial cover while you
are in them and block LOS when you are on the other side of them. If you
use this property of trees to your advantage, it can be useful.

@item Water in not so good. They may provide cover, but the dangers are
much worse. Water slows you down a lot. You also have the possibility of
falling over and taking damege. You do not want to give these free hits to your
enemy. When you get hit while in the water, you will be hit in the top part
of your Mech. This can be very dangerous. Water can be beneficial in that
if you are fallen (DROP) in water, the enemy cannot see you, so you can
recharge your weapons without worrying about getting hit. However, once you
STAND to fire, they will all peg you. [Note: Commonly known as 'Pop And
Drop' (PAD/P&D), this is indeed a useful tactic, especially for ambushes
where you have one or more mechs spotting range and targets for you.
However, it considered extremly dishonourable by the Clans, and generally
cowardly by everyone else.] In the mean time they will be moving
continually closer. The only time water is good is when you have a few
buddies with you, or if the enemy does not know you are there. It is
possible to hide in water while the enemy passes by and then jump up and
hit them in the back. You must have teammates telling you where they are
for this to work, though.

@item Hills are questionable. If they happen to be on the other side of the
peak from you, you will get partial cover, but your slower speed tets them
get closer. Wether you want this or not depends on your strategy. They can
be useful to walk on/over, but it will take you longer to move away if you
need to.

@end itemize

@end itemize

There are scores of different situations and each one will use the terrain
in a different way. There are many strategies to using it, and the only way
to learn all is through experience. These are just a couple examples.

@node Speed
@section Speed
@cindex Speed

The speed of your and your enemy's Mechs will play a large part in
determining your strategy.

@itemize @bullet
@item If you are slower than your opponent, you will have to plot your
heading to be ahead of his current direction. Move to intercept his course
to close the distance. One trick that you might find useful is to split the
difference between their bearing and heading. Thus, if they are bearing 0
from you and moving heading 120, you would go heading 60 to intercept them.

@item If you are faster then your opponent, you want to use this ability to
your advantage.

@itemize @bullet
@item Assuming you are a mobile lance (i.e. not sitting in a forest or
lake), you should be at top speed almost all the time. This makes it very
difficult for them to hit you.

@item Slow to wlaking speed to fire. You should know your walking speed
from the Preparation phase. One can use the speed command (options status) to
determine walking speed. Slowing will give you a better chance to hit. It
is a good idea to SIGHT your weapons so you know when you have reached your
walking speed. As soonas you see the ToHit go down a notch, fire what you
want to fire and immediately speed back up to top speed.

@item Slow to turn sharply. Be careful with this, as they can hit you more
easily when you are moving slower. The best time to do this is when you are
out of their LOS.

@item Walking backwards while facing your enemy can be a useful tool,
especially when you are faster than they. This keeps them in your forward
weapons arc while keeping your distance. They are a few points to keep in
mind, though.

@itemize @bullet
@item Know your maximum backward speed in relation to their maximum forward
speed. Do not let them close in too quickly.

@item Always have a destination in mind, even when walking backwards. It is
a good idea to change your heading so that you are walking back behind a
hill. In this way, once you are out of sight, you can turn and run away to
maintain the distance you want.

@item Be very careful about changing from backwards to forwards. If you are
in their sight, they will fire when your speed gets to zero in the
transition stage. They have a much easier time hitting you once you have
slowed. You cannot always avoid this, though. Just be careful.

@end itemize

@item Keeping your distance with your speed is a good thing, but if you
find yourself just outside of a lower range bracket, you should be prepared
to close in and fire just after they have fired their weapons. Do this
especially if they have just missed you.

@end itemize

@end itemize

@node Torso Twists
@section Torso Twists
@cindex Torso Twists

Using torso twists is a technique all on its own.

@itemize @bullet
@item For the most part, you should always turn to keep them in your
forward weapons arc. This lets you run diagonally away from them and still
be able to fire all your weapons.

@item If you are moving directly away, you can turn to the right and have
them in your right weapon arc and fire your weapons located on the right
sied. You should know these weapons from the Preperation stege. Thenyou can
turn to the left and do the same with your left weapons.

@item Turning your torso allows you to control which side of your mech is
facing your enemy. By using this along with adjusting your heading, you can
leave your wounded sections away from them, and let them hit your good side
for a while. Evening out your armor hits is a great technique. All it takes
is a few hits in the same section to render a Mech helpless.

@item Along the same line, you may wish to face directly away from the
enemy. Doing this will let you fire your weapons, if any. However, this is
why you should have paid close attention to how much armor you have in your
rear. Your rear is the most vulnerable spot. You should be extremly
cautious when turning your back on an enemy. It is not necessarily bad to
take a few hits in the back under certain circumstances. It helps to even
out things even more. Just understand that you have to watch it very
carefully.

@end itemize

@node The End
@section The End
@cindex The End

And thus we bring to a close the Battle Bible. If used in conjunction with
a good instructor, this will take you very far. Good luck, and my honour be
with you always.

@node Frequently Asked Questions
@chapter Frequently Asked Questions
@cindex Frequently Asked Questions

The answers to the Frequently Asked Questions are
based on the most current BattleTech rules as found in the BattleTech 
Compendium: The Rules of Warfare, Third Printing (softcover). 
Each question appears under the name of the chapter containing the 
information most closely related to the answer.

PLAYING THE GAME

Initiative

Q: Can a player end up moving more than one unit after his opponent has
finished moving all his units?

A: Yes. When one side outnumbers the other, the player with more units will
end up moving MORE than one unit last if he wins Initiative.

MOVEMENT

Falling

Q: Do I have to add in all the standard modifiers when making a Piloting
Skill Roll to avoid damage to my pilot when falling?

A: Yes. It is a Piloting Skill Roll, and so all normal modifiers apply.

Skidding

Q: Can a unit, after having skidded, continue its normal movement if
it has MP remaining?

A: No. A skid ends the unit's movement for the phase, even if it has MP
remaining.

Q: If my 'Mech has fallen and is skidding and it runs into a building or
mountain before it stops, do I take some type of charging damage?

A: No. The building or mountain would stop your skid, regardless of the
height of either obstacle or the construction factor of the building. 
However, a building would receive damage from the skidding 'Mech per 
the normal Charging rules.

COMBAT

Critical Damage

Q: Does an Inner Sphere 'Mech with an XL engine have its engine destroyed
if it loses all the internal structure of either its right or left torso?
What about if it has an ammo explosion in one of those locations and it
has CASE?

A: Yes. Regardless of where an engine receives its 3 hits-in the right,
center or left torso-if an engine receives 3 critical hits it is destroyed.

Firing Weapons

Q: If one of my 'Mech's arms is destroyed, can I prop up my prone 'Mech
with the other arm and fire my torso-mounted weapons?

A: No. A 'Mech must have both of its arms intact in order to fire while
prone. While prone, it can fire into its normal arcs, but cannot torso twist.

Heat

Q: What happens when my 'Mech shuts down?

A: When a 'Mech shuts down, it cannot move or torso twist. In addition,
all of its systems, including weapons and all electronics-C3 Slave or 
Master, ECM, etc.-are inoperative until the 'Mech restarts.

Line of Sight

Q: If my unit is firing on another unit that has partial cover but I
am an elevation level higher than him, does he still have partial cover?

A: No. No unit can have partial cover from an attacking unit that is at
a higher elevation level.

Q: If a 'Mech on Level 0 terrain is prone and adjacent to a Level 1 hill,
is the 'Mech in a dead zone?

A: Yes. Only a STANDING 'Mech adds 1 to its elevation for LOS; prone 'Mechs
do not.

PHYSICAL ATTACKS

Q: Can more than one unit make a Charge or Death From Above attack against
the same enemy unit in the same turn?

A: No. Once a unit has declared a Charge or Death From Above attack on another
unit, no other unit may declare an additional Charge or Death From Above
attack on that unit.

Q: Does a Club or Hatchet attack hit on the BattleMech Punch Location Table?

A: No. Use the BattleMech Hit Location Table to determine the hit location
of a Club or Hatchet attack. However, Club and Hatchet attacks are subject
to the Different Elevation rules, as usual.

Q: If I charge or push a BattleMech that, when displaced, would move into
an adjacent hex that is more than 3 elevation levels higher, would it still
move there?

A: No. A unit subject to a Push, Charge or Death From Above attack will
always be displaced unless the rules prevent that displacement, for example,
a BattleMech unit changing more than 3 elevation levels up. In such situations,
neither unit would move. If the attack is a Charge or Death From Above,
only the normal damage for that type of attack would be assigned. No additional
damage would occur. Note that a unit CAN be pushed DOWN more elevations
than the rules allow for legal movement-which would result in an accidental
fall.

Q: If I announce a Charging or Death From Above attack against a prone target,
do I receive the -2 to-hit modifier for being adjacent to a prone target?

A: Yes. Although you start your attack in the Movement Phase, at the beginning
of the Physical Attack Phase when you actually make the to-hit roll, you
are adjacent to the target.

Q: My BattleMech was designed with no hand or lower arm actuators (for example,
the OBK-M10 O-Bakemono). Do I still receive the negative modifiers for the
to-hit roll and when doing damage in a Punching attack?

A: Yes. However, the 'Mech suffers no penalty to Weapon attacks from those
arms.

VEHICLES

Q: What happens when a "critical" result is rolled on a Vehicle
Hit Location Table?

A: Like the critical result on the BattleMech Hit Location Table, this provides
a chance for one or more critical hits. Roll on the Determining Critical
Hits Table. If any critical hits are scored, determine their effects on
the appropriate Vehicle Critical Hit Table.

INFANTRY

Q: Can battle armor units enter water of Depth 1 or deeper?

A: No. Battle armor units must follow the same rules as other infantry regarding
movement and terrain restrictions, except as specifically noted in the rules.

Q: When infantry-standard or power armor-dismounts at the end of the Movement
Phase, will they receive the movement modifier for the number of hexes that
the carrying unit moved when resolving fire?

A: No.

Q: Do battle armor units take damage from flamers and fire?

A: Yes. Although some of the BattleTech fiction indicates that battle armor
units are immune to fire, the actual game rules do not protect them.

Q: My Point of elementals enters a mined hex and it explodes. Does each
elemental take the damage or does the unit as a whole take the damage?

A: The elementals as a unit (Point) take the damage.

CONSTRUCTION

Q: Can I mount two engines in a BattleMech or vehicle?

A: No.

Q: Can I design a BattleMech with a heavier chassis (Internal Structure)
than is required? For example, I am designing a 55-ton 'Mech and wish to
add a 6-ton chassis.

A: No.

Q: When constructing a 'Mech, can I allocate Triple Strength Myomer anywhere
on the 'Mech and split the criticals up between different locations?

A: Yes.

Q: When constructing a 'Mech, can I allocate MASC anywhere on the 'Mech
and split the criticals up between different locations?

A: MASC can be allocated anywhere on the 'Mech, but the criticals cannot
be split up between locations.

EQUIPMENT

Q: Can an anti-missile system be used against an Arrow IV homing missile?

A: No. Despite its name, the Arrow IV is an artillery weapon, not a missile
weapon. An anti-missile system is only effective against missile weapons.
The missile category is listed on the Weapons and Equipment Table, and includes
LRMs, SRMs, Streak SRMs, and Narc Missile Beacons.

Q: When constructing a Clan 'Mech with a targeting computer, do all eligible
direct-fire weapons have to be tied to the targeting computer?

A: Yes. Note that Machine Guns are not eligible weapons; only Lasers, PPCs,
Gauss rifles and Autocannons.

Q: What happens when a MASC critical location on a 'Mech is hit?

A: Per the normal rules for equipment, regardless of the number of critical
spaces MASC occupies, the first critical hit destroys the MASC.

Q: If I have an AMS and my opponent fires multiple missile packs at my 'Mech,
can I choose which one to try and shoot down? What if I have multiple AMS?

A: No. Whichever missile pack your opponent declares first-even if you have
multiple AMS-all your AMS will fire upon it.

Q: If my 'Mech has a Gauss rifle that explodes in a location containing
CASE, would the CASE protect the 'Mech from further damage just like in
an ammo explosion?

A: Yes. Note the pilot also takes 2 points of damage, just like in an ammo
explosion.

Q: I have two 'Mechs linked by a C3 computer system. One of my 'Mechs is
far away, while my other 'Mech is close to my opponent's 'Mech (which has
a ECM suite). If I am trying to hit my opponent's 'Mech using the C3 computer
system, will the ECM suite block it?

A: It all depends on whether or not one of the two attacking 'Mechs actually
enters the ECM suite "bubble". In other words, if the closer unit
is within the 6-hex range of the ECM suite, its "connection" to
the other 'Mech has been broken. However, if the unit is 7 hexes or more
away from the ECM-equipped unit, the "connection" is intact and
the first 'Mech may use the C3 computer system to target its opponent.

SPECIAL CASE RULES

Q: Can I reverse my 'Mech's arms when it is prone?

A: No.

